---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About - Abject"
  description="Abject is an open-source, peer-to-peer desktop platform for local-first AI objects. Built by mempko, successor to Fire★. GPL-3.0. No company, no investors, no surveillance."
>
  <Header />
  <main class="about">
    <div class="about-container">

      <header class="about-hero">
        <p class="about-eyebrow">// ABOUT</p>
        <h1>The Grass Still Grows. Now It Thinks.</h1>
        <p class="about-thesis">
          Abject is an open-source desktop platform for AI objects that live on your own machine,
          find each other over peer-to-peer connections, and explain themselves in plain English.
          It is licensed under GPL-3.0. It is not a company. It is not selling you a subscription.
          It is a thing that exists because it should.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section class="about-section">
        <h2>Why This Exists</h2>
        <p>
          Most people never use a computer to compute. They read, they watch, they scroll:
          consumption, inside sealed apps somebody else wrote. That is not a law of nature;
          it is an information monopoly. Software stayed hard to make, so making it stayed
          a profession. LLMs just cracked that open. For the first time, anyone who can say
          what they want can have software that is personal, connected, and theirs. Abject
          exists so that happens on your machine, under your control, with nobody collecting rent.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every popular AI agent framework today puts a single planner on top and tools beneath.
          That works for short demos and breaks on the things you actually want it to do for weeks
          at a time. Hierarchies snap; meshes route around damage. The internet has known this
          for fifty years.
        </p>
        <p>
          There is also a longer bet here. Sixty years of software has been pyramid building:
          applications on frameworks on libraries on operating systems, each layer taxed by the
          one below, complexity growing until the parts no longer fit in a context window. Most
          of the industry is using LLMs to stack the pyramid faster. Abject uses them to start
          from a smaller foundation instead: message-passing objects, with the LLM handling the
          ambiguity that rigid interfaces never could.
        </p>
        <p>
          So Abject takes the pattern that already runs the world (TCP/IP, Smalltalk's objects,
          Erlang's actors, the cells in your body) and adds one small primitive: every object can
          explain itself to any other object in plain English. The LLM is just a service one
          object asks when it needs to think. The architecture is older than the LLM.
        </p>
        <p>
          The result is a system you own. Your machine runs your agents. Your tokens come from
          your account, or from a local model that costs nothing. Your goals live on your peers,
          not on someone else's server. Anthropic can change its pricing at midnight and your
          abjects will not notice.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="about-section">
        <h2>Who Built It</h2>
        <p>
          Abject is built by <strong>Maxim Khailo</strong> (<a href="https://github.com/mempko" target="_blank" rel="noopener">mempko</a> on GitHub),
          a software engineer who has spent years building open-source distributed systems.
        </p>
        <p>
          The motivation predates the project. Max came to the United States in the late 80s
          as a refugee from the Donbas, in the former Soviet Union. The first computer was a
          hand-me-down from a friend of his father's; the programming education was standing in
          bookstores memorizing tech books there was no money to buy. Somewhere in there he found
          Engelbart and Kay and the idea that a computer is a rocketship for the mind.
          Abject is that idea, paid forward.
        </p>
        <p>
          Before Abject came <a href="https://firestr.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fire★</a>,
          a peer-to-peer platform for creating and sharing distributed applications, written in C++ and Lua,
          released under the GNU GPL. Fire★ called what it did <em>Grass Computing</em>:
          software you can touch, shape, and share directly. No cloud. No landlords. It proved
          the vision works. It also proved that the vision needs an LLM to negotiate between objects
          built by people who never met. That gap is what Abject closes.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="about-section">
        <h2>The Ideas, Longform</h2>
        <ul class="about-list">
          <li><strong><a href="https://blog.mempko.com/an-abject-horror/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">An Abject Horror</a>.</strong> The announcement: why agents are the wrong abstraction, and what a self-aware object runtime is.</li>
          <li><strong><a href="https://blog.mempko.com/entering-the-architecture-age/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Entering the Architecture Age</a>.</strong> The software pyramid, the Window Tax, and why the big idea is messaging.</li>
          <li><strong><a href="https://blog.mempko.com/let-the-information-monopolies-crumble/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Let the Information Monopolies Crumble!</a></strong> The human case: computers are for computing, and everyone should get to.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="about-section">
        <h2>What This Isn't</h2>
        <ul class="about-list">
          <li><strong>Not a startup.</strong> No investors. No board. No exit strategy. No roadmap to monetize you.</li>
          <li><strong>Not a SaaS.</strong> Your data, your tokens, your machine. The signaling server is open source; run your own.</li>
          <li><strong>Not telemetry-funded.</strong> The system makes no calls home. Add a <code>WS_PORT</code> and that's the only network it asks for.</li>
          <li><strong>Not closed.</strong> GPL-3.0-or-later. Fork it. Modify it. Ship it. Just keep it free.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="about-section">
        <h2>How To Reach Me</h2>
        <ul class="about-list">
          <li><strong>Email:</strong> <a href="mailto:max@mempko.com">max@mempko.com</a></li>
          <li><strong>GitHub:</strong> <a href="https://github.com/mempko/abject" target="_blank" rel="noopener">mempko/abject</a> (issues, PRs welcome)</li>
          <li><strong>Reddit:</strong> <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/AbjectWorld/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">r/AbjectWorld</a></li>
          <li><strong>Discord:</strong> <a href="https://discord.gg/B75AeYUYcF" target="_blank" rel="noopener">join here</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="about-coda">
        Abject is a long-term project. It will be slow. It will be weird. It will keep being free.
      </p>

    </div>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .about {
    min-height: 100vh;
    padding-top: 96px;
    padding-bottom: 4rem;
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
  }

  .about-container {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 0 1.5rem;
  }

  .about-hero {
    margin-bottom: 3.5rem;
  }

  .about-eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--eldritch);
    letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .about-hero h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 2.6rem);
    line-height: 1.2;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .about-thesis {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .about-section {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .about-section h2 {
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .about-section p {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .about-section p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .about-section a {
    color: var(--eldritch-dim);
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(43, 204, 110, 0.3);
    padding-bottom: 1px;
    transition: color 0.2s, border-color 0.2s;
  }

  .about-section a:hover {
    color: var(--eldritch);
    border-bottom-color: var(--eldritch);
  }

  .about-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .about-list li {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    padding: 0.75rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .about-list li:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .about-list strong {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .about-list code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--eldritch);
    background: var(--eldritch-glow);
    padding: 0.1rem 0.35rem;
    border-radius: 3px;
  }

  .about-coda {
    margin-top: 4rem;
    text-align: center;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-dim);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }
</style>
